2 of 4

Fig. S3. Inﬂuence of the endogenous circadian system on cardiovascular reactivity to exercise. Cosine models of reactivity to exercise revealed signiﬁcant circadian rhythmicity for HF, pNN50, and SBP, and signiﬁcant second harmonics of the circadian rhythmicity for epinephrine and norepinephrine. The other variables did not have statistically signiﬁcant rhythmicity (P > 0.05). Although a circadian variation in the magnitude of reactivity to exercise (vertical difference between red and black line) can be observed in Fig. 2, the statistically signiﬁcant 12-h rhythmicity is more apparent in this ﬁgure because this is based on the cosine model that uses circadian phase data with a resolution of 1 circadian degree, whereas Fig. 2 shows the data grouped into 60° windows, which causes slight visual differences that do not affect the statistical analysis (all statistical analysis based on cosinor models). Note, so that higher putative risk is upwards
for all variables, the y axes for the vagal markers HF and pNN50 are inverted, i.e., upwards corresponds to vagal withdrawal. This is different from the orientation of these variables in Fig. 2 of the main manuscript. Symbols as in Fig. 2. *Timing of the peak position for signiﬁcant fundamental circadian cycle; #timing of the peak positions for signiﬁcant second harmonic of circadian cycle.

